Net Atlas Ultimate is a '''neon-themed''' interactive '''3D world explorer''' that displays '''websites by country''' using a '''spinning globe''', '''visual effects''', '''flags''', '''icons''', and '''categories'''. It is built using '''Three.js''' and '''three-globe''' for the 3D globe, and '''world-atlas TopoJSON''' for real country polygons. The application features an '''orbital visual style''' with a '''starfield''', '''layered neon orbits''', and an '''atmosphere halo'''. By clicking on a country, users can fetch live '''metadata''' from '''RESTCountries''', view the country's '''flag''' and '''stats''', and explore '''websites''' defined in the '''websites-by-country.json''' file.

== Overview ==
Net Atlas Ultimate is designed to visualize lists of websites that can be assembled using various online resources, such as '''Wikipedia''', '''BuiltWith''', '''all.site''', and '''internet-map.net'''. However, the '''browser frontend''' does not '''scrape''' these sites directly, as many of them have '''Terms of Service''' that restrict scraping. Instead, users are expected to use their own '''backend''' or '''CLI scripts''' to collect '''URLs''' and generate the '''websites-by-country.json''' file, which is then rendered on the '''orbital globe'''.

== Features ==
The key features of Net Atlas Ultimate include:
* A '''spinning 3D globe''' with real country polygons
* An '''orbital visual style''' with a starfield, layered neon orbits, and an atmosphere halo
* '''Click-to-explore''' functionality for countries, which displays live metadata, flags, and stats
* '''Website favicons''', '''country flags''', and '''TLD-based categories'''
* Support for '''neon''', '''glassmorphism''', '''CRT scanlines''', and '''hover bloom''' visual effects

== Installation ==
To deploy Net Atlas Ultimate to '''GitHub Pages''', follow these steps:
1. Create a new repository and add the required files: '''index.html''', '''style.css''', '''script.js''', '''websites-by-country.json''', '''LICENSE''', '''.gitignore''', and '''README.md'''
2. Push the changes to GitHub
3. Enable GitHub Pages by going to Settings → Pages → source = '''main''' / root
4. The site will be available at '''https://<username>.github.io/<repo>/'''

== Data ==
The '''websites-by-country.json''' file is used to store the list of websites for each country. The file should be in the following format:
```json
{
  "AU": [
    { "url": "https://abc.net.au", "category": "media" },
    { "url": "https://www.australia.gov.au", "category": "government" }
  ],
  "US": [
    { "url": "https://www.whitehouse.gov", "category": "government" },
    { "url": "https://www.nasa.gov", "category": "science" }
  ]
}
```
The keys are '''ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country codes''' (AU, US, JP, DE, etc.). Users are responsible for populating this file using their own backend or CLI scripts, respecting the '''Terms of Service''' of the websites being scraped.